tsland","Framershein, Alzey-Worms, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany":"Duitsland","Framersheim, Alzey, Hessen, Germany":"Framersheim, Alzey, Hessen, Duitsland","Germany":"Duitsland"},"en":{"about 1660–before 1688":"about 1660–before 1688","1650–1693":"1650–1693","1678–1752":"1678–1752","1680–1737":"1680–1737","1660–1688":"1660–1688","before 1688":"before 1688","1660":"1660","1693":"1693","1680":"1680","about 24 September 1678":"about 24 September 1678","1678":"1678","1688":"1688","1752":"1752","about 1678":"about 1678","1650":"1650","about 1660":"about 1660","1737":"1737","about 1680":"about 1680","Framersheim, Rheinland-Pfalz, Germany":"Framersheim, Alzey-Worms, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany","Framersheim, Alzey-Worms, Rheinland-Pfalz, Germany":"Framersheim, Alzey-Worms, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany","Framershein, Alzey-Worms, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany":"Germany","Framersheim, Alzey, Hessen, Germany":"Framersheim, Alzey, Hesse, Germany","Germany":"Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wendel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Helmut, Otto, Aloys, Bodo, Egon, Elke, Erwin, Frieda, Gerhard, Jurgen, Katharina.","German, Swedish, Danish, and Dutch: from the German personal name <i>Wendel</i>, a pet form of a short form, <i>Wando</i>, of a compound ancient Germanic name beginning with <i>wand</i> ‘to go, to migrate’.","German: metonymic occupational name for a turner, from Middle High German <i>wendel</i> ‘to turn’ or Middle Low German <i>wendelen</i> ‘to turn, twist’."],"variants":[{"name":"Wendelin","meanings":["South German: from the personal name <i>Wendelin</i>, a pet form of   Wendel  . <i>Wendelin</i> is the name of a Christian saint venerated in the Saarland, Germany.","Swedish: habitational name from a place called Vendel + the adjectival suffix <i>-in</i>, a derivative of Latin <i>-in(i)us</i> ‘relating to’. In some cases it may also be of German origin (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Wendl","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans.","South German (Bavaria and Austria): variant of   Wendel  ."]},{"name":"Wendler","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Arno, Kurt, Siegbert, Claus, Erwin, Ewald, Gerd, Hans, Helmut, Helmuth, Otto.","German:","from Middle High German <i>wandeler</i> ‘traveler on foot’ (Middle Low German <i>wendeler</i>), hence a nickname for a pilgrim or an occupational name for a peddler."]},{"name":"Wandell","meanings":["Variant of   Wendel  ."]},{"name":"Wendell","meanings":["German, Swedish, and Danish: variant of   Wendel   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this (which can be also of Dutch origin). The surname <i>Wendell</i> is (very) rare in Germany, Sweden, and Denmark.","History: A prominent New Netherland (now NY) merchant family of this name descended from a colonist from Emden, Germany, which was part of the Netherlands in the 17th century."]},{"name":"Wendle","meanings":["South German: variant of   Wendel   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Wandel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Gerhard, Horst, Klaus.","German and Dutch: variant of   Wendel  .","Flemish (<b>De Wandel</b>): nickname for a pilgrim or an occupational name for a peddler, or a nickname for an unreliable person."]},{"name":"Windels","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Lothar.","German: patronymic from (a variant of) the personal name   Wendel  .","North German: metronymic from a short form of the female personal names <i>Windelheid</i> or <i>Windelmod</i>."]},{"name":"Wendling","meanings":["German:","habitational name from any of numerous places called Wendling, notably in Bavaria, or a place called Wendlingen, for example near Stuttgart.","(Westphalia): patronymic from the personal name <i>Wendel</i> (see   Wendel   1)."]}]},{"name":"Johann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Vernacular form of   Johannes ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]},{"name":"Jacob","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, from Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>. This was borne by perhaps the most important of all the patriarchs in the Book of Genesis. Jacob was the father of twelve sons, who gave their names to the twelve tribes of Israel. He was the son of Isaac and Rebecca and twin brother of Esau. According to the story in Genesis, he was the cunning younger twin, who persuaded his brother Esau to part with his right to his inheritance in exchange for a bowl of soup (‘a mess of pottage’). Later, he tricked his blind and dying father into blessing him in place of Esau. The derivation of the name has been much discussed. It is traditionally explained as being derived from Hebrew <i>akev</i> ‘heel’ and to have meant ‘heel grabber’, because when Jacob was born ‘his hand took hold of Esau's heel’ (Genesis 25:26). This is interpreted later in the Bible as ‘supplanter’ Esau himself remarks, ‘Is he not rightly named Jacob? for he has supplanted me these two times’ (Genesis 27:36). <i>Jacob</i> is especially common as a Jewish given name, although it also became very popular among the Puritans from the 16th century onwards, and has again been widely used since the 1990s.  Compare  James ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Johann Jacob Wendel was born about 1660, in Germany. She married Johann Jacob Wendel about 1678, in Germany. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died before 1688, in Framersheim, Alzey-Worms, Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany."},"et":{"about 1660–before 1688":"umbes 1660–enne 1688","1650–1693":"1650–1693","1678–1752":"1678–1752","168